# Fluff Date: 2026-03-08 18:30:06
<overview>
<p>The J-27 Trailer is a powered companion vehicle developed by the Republic Institute of Strategic Combat as a platform for their experimental viral jammer technology. Unlike the standard unpowered J-27 trailer, these ten-ton wheeled units mount their own fusion engines and heavy ferro-fibrous armor, allowing them to operate independently once positioned. The trailers were conceived as part of a broader RISC initiative to deploy electronic warfare capabilities using existing, inconspicuous military vehicles. Their small size and unremarkable appearance made them ideal for placement at chokepoints and strategic bottlenecks where they could disrupt enemy electronics without drawing immediate attention or suspicion from opposing forces.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>Each RISC trailer variant mounts a ten-rated fusion engine providing the power necessary for its electronic warfare payload. Heavy ferro-fibrous armor offers protection far beyond what the vehicle's appearance suggests, with sixteen points distributed across its hull. A trailer hitch allows the units to be towed into position by standard J-27 tractors or other vehicles before being activated independently. The fusion powerplant provides sustained energy output required by the jammer systems, which draw considerably more power than conventional electronic equipment.</p><p>The viral jammer technology itself is volatile, with a destructive failure rate essentially guaranteed from the moment of activation. Each deployment is effectively a one-time use that must be carefully timed for maximum effect. While other RISC technology has been known for general unreliability, the jammers represent a deliberately accepted trade of longevity for overwhelming electronic disruption capability. The cost of mass-producing the jammers has remained prohibitive, limiting deployment to high-value strategic operations.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>The Decoy configuration of the RISC trailer supports decoy viral jammer operations, broadcasting false electronic signatures designed to confuse and overwhelm enemy targeting and communications systems. It entered service around 3136 as part of the initial RISC viral jammer deployment program based at the Proving Ground Liberté complex on Terra.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>RISC technology spent two decades at the fringes of military application, its impact limited to brief battlefield surprises. The viral jammer program changed that calculus. During the Jihad, the Word of Blake's industrial-scale deployment of improved C3 technologies made dedicated electronic countermeasures nearly mandatory throughout the Inner Sphere. The BattleMechs that defended the Republic's Prefectures became saturated with electronic warfare equipment, and battlefields were blanketed in sensor interference.</p><p>When the Republic's covert raiding campaign began, control of the electronic battlespace became a key priority. RISC's decoy jammer specifically targeted enemy counter-measures, with documented raids from Augustine to Kessel demonstrating their disruptive potential. The overwhelming power of these jammers sharply undermined the reliability of advanced electronics across the board, contributing to a decline in electronic warfare systems appearing in new BattleMech designs.</p><p>RISC devised a solution focused on an unlikely platform. The J-27 ordnance transport's spacious chassis lent itself to easy modification, and the jammers could be mounted on a powered trailer positioned at strategic locations. During Operation Mercury, many trailer-based jammers were deployed, with the homing variant proving particularly effective at neutralizing Clan materiel. Clan Sea Fox expressed interest in acquiring jammer production capability, though the question of whether to enable such proliferation remained politically contentious within the Republic's leadership.</p>
</history>

